  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: **placement** (introducing illegal funds into the financial system), **layering** (concealing the source of the funds through complex transactions), and **integration** (making the funds appear legitimate).\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime because it enables other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud, to thrive by disguising the illicit origins of the funds. Most countries have stringent laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities.\n\nInternational organizations, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, also play a key role in setting global standards and promoting effective implementation of anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist financing measures. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
